    <p>
      Save reinforcement learning using curriculum learning by a trained teacher.
      A NI-Project<d-footnote id="d-footnote-1">Neural Information Processing Project</d-footnote>
      at TU Berlin<d-footnote id="d-footnote-1"><a href="https://www.tu.berlin/">Technical University of Berlin</a></d-footnote>
      based on <d-cite key="Turchetta2020SafeRL"></d-cite>.
    </p>
  </d-title>

  <d-article>

    <h2>Introduction</h2>

    <h4>Key Ideas</h4>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>A teacher trains a student to solve a task</li>
        <li>The teacher keeps the student safe during training</li>
        <li>For this, the teacher is given a set of pre-defined interventions and learns to apply them optimally$\rightarrow\emph{curriculum policy}$</li>
        <li>Interventions are pairs of trigger states and transitions guiding the student back into a safe state</li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <h4>Our Approach</h4>
    <p>
      We compare the students trained by the Optimized curriculum policy from the paper <d-cite key="Turchetta2020SafeRL"/></d-cite>
      to students trained with our own curriculum policies.
    </p>

    <h2>Background</h2>

    <h4>Constrained Markov Decision Process</h4>

    <ul>
      <li>
        The student is a RL agent trained in a CMDP
        $ \mathcal{M} = \langle \mathcal{S},\mathcal{A},\mathcal{P},r,\mathcal{D} \rangle $
      </li>
      <li>$\mathcal{S}, \mathcal{A}$: State and action space</li>
      <li>$\mathcal{P}(s'|s,a)$: Transition kernel</li>
      <li>$r:\mathcal{S}\times\mathcal{A}\times\mathcal{S}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$: Reward function</li>
      <li>$\mathcal{D}$: Set of unsafe terminal states</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Curriculum Induction for Safe RL</h4>

    <ul>
      <li>In CISR, the teacher gets a set $\mathcal{I}$ of interventions $\{ \langle \mathcal{D}_i, \mathcal{T}_i \rangle \}_{i=1}^K$ as input, which consist of \emph{trigger states} $\mathcal{D}_i \subset \mathcal{S}$ and reset distributions $\mathcal{T}_i: \mathcal{S} \rightarrow \Delta_{\mathcal{S} \backslash \mathcal{D}_i}$</li>
      <li><b>Curriculum</b>: Sequence of CMDPs $\mathcal{M}_{i_1},...,\mathcal{M}_{i_{N_s}}$, where during the $n^{\text{th}}$ curriculum step, the student interacts with the CMDP $\mathcal{M}_{i_n}$ induced by an intervention $i_n\in\mathcal{I}$</li>
      <li><b>Curriculum Policy</b>: A curriculum policy $\pi^T: \mathcal{H} \rightarrow \mathcal{I}$ maps the teacher's observation history of statistics $\phi(\pi_1),...,\phi(\pi_{n-1})\in\mathcal{H}$ about the student's policy to an intervention at the start of the $n^{\text{th}}$ curriculum step</li>
      <li>For curriculum policies independent of the student's policy (e.g. SR, HR, Back or Incremental), this can be simplified to a mapping $\pi^T:[N_s]\rightarrow \mathcal{I}$</li>
    </ul>

